  "prompt": "What are the various Incarnations of Lord Vishnu and what is going to be the last Incarnation of Lord Vishnu?",
  "response": "Lord Vishnu, one of the principal deities in Hinduism, is known for his various incarnations, collectively referred to as \"Dashavatara.\" The term \"Dashavatara\" translates to \"ten avatars\" and represents the ten principal avatars of Vishnu that he takes to restore cosmic order. Here are the ten incarnations:\n\n1. **Matsya (The Fish)**: Vishnu took the form of a fish to save the sage Manu and the Vedas from a great flood.\n\n2. **Kurma (The Tortoise)**: In this incarnation, Vishnu became a tortoise to support Mount Mandara, which was used as a churning rod during the churning of the ocean (Samudra Manthan) to obtain the nectar of immortality.\n\n3. **Varaha (The Boar)**: Vishnu assumed the form of a boar to rescue the Earth (personified as the goddess Bhudevi) from the demon Hiranyaksha, who had submerged it in the cosmic ocean.\n\n4. **Narasimha (The Man-Lion)**: Vishnu took on a half-man, half-lion form to defeat the demon Hiranyakashipu, who was immune to being killed by man or beast.\n\n5. **Vamana (The Dwarf)**: In this avatar, Vishnu appeared as a dwarf Brahmin to subdue the demon king Bali by asking for three paces of land and then expanding to cover the entire universe in three steps.\n\n6. **Parashurama (The Warrior with an Axe)**: Vishnu incarnated as Parashurama, a Brahmin warrior, to rid the world of corrupt Kshatriyas (warriors) who were oppressing the people.\n\n7. **Rama (The Prince of Ayodhya)**: Vishnu took the form of Lord Rama, the hero of the Ramayana, to defeat the demon king Ravana and rescue his wife Sita.\n\n8. **Krishna (The Divine Cowherd)**: In this incarnation, Vishnu played a crucial role in the Mahabharata, delivering the Bhagavad Gita to Arjuna and performing various miracles.\n\n9. **Buddha (The Enlightened One)**: Some Hindu traditions include Gautama Buddha as an avatar of Vishnu, emphasizing the idea of compassion and enlightenment. However, this inclusion is debated among different sects of Hinduism.\n\n10. **Kalki (The Future Warrior)**: The last avatar of Vishnu, Kalki, is prophesied to appear in the future. He is expected to come riding a white horse, wielding a sword, to end the current age of darkness and corruption (Kali Yuga), restore righteousness (Dharma), and establish a new age of truth (Satya Yuga).\n\nAccording to Hindu belief, Kalki's arrival is anticipated to happen at the end of Kali Yuga, which is the current age we are in now, and it will mark the end of the cycle of creation and the beginning of a new cycle.",
